{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fbd4851f-47a4-4a43-858b-d2f79c0a1681","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores typically land in /cores/\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Note: SIP (System Integrity Protection) may prevent core dump generation for some paths.\n\n4. **`log show`** for system-level crash info:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"YourAppName\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and faulting address.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1a951dc0-2ad8-4043-a3e9-027e225ceee9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":326,"requestId":"5FC0:27C56C:D876CE:FBB119:69EACA66"},"id":"28fd7951-3e58-4e32-8212-f00e10159890","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:42:07.192Z","parentId":"99c53fa4-129b-4e48-954b-792827a77e9b"}
